<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12053n"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12053n">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12053n"> 53(n)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ Aubert &amp; Firmin</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">C&apos;est ainsi qu&apos;aux premiers temps du monast&egrave;re, deux religieux furent atteints d&apos;une fi&egrave;vre fort aigu&euml;. L&apos;un d&apos;eux pria ses confr&egrave;res &laquo;de <font color="green">[50]</font> laver la t&ecirc;te de saint Aubert et de lui donner &agrave; boire la liqueur dont on l&apos;avait lav&eacute;e <font color="green">[1]</font>&raquo;. Il but et il fut gu&eacute;ri. L&apos;autre moine, trop douillet &laquo;et mal fortifi&eacute; des sens&raquo;, disait qu&apos;il aimait mieux mourir que de boire une liqueur qui avait &eacute;t&eacute; distill&eacute;e par la t&ecirc;te d&apos;un homme mort. II mourut huit jours apr&egrave;s <font color="green">[2]</font>. <br><font color="green">[1]</font> Le chef de saint Aubert est conserv&eacute;, de nos jours, &agrave; la basilique de Saint-Gervais d&apos;Avranches. La tradition veut que l&apos;archange saint Michel, au cours d&apos;une apparition &agrave; saint Aubert, enfon&ccedil;a son doigt dans le cr&acirc;ne de l&apos;&eacute;v&ecirc;que qui restait sourd &agrave; ses commandements. Cette curieuse relique nous montre que les os du cr&acirc;ne et de la face sont tous attenants. Il n&apos;y manque que l&apos;os maxillaire inf&eacute;rieur et des dents &agrave; la m&acirc;choire sup&eacute;rieure: &laquo;A la premi&egrave;re inspection, on remarque vers le milieu de l&apos;os pari&eacute;tal droit, une ouverture oblongue, d&apos;arri&egrave;re en avant, assez grande pour qu&apos;on puisse y introduire le pouce. Les bords de celle ouverture sont un peu amincis, lisses au dehors comme au- dedans. Rien dans le pourtour de cette ouverture, ni dans toute l&apos;&eacute;tendue de l&apos;os o&ugrave; elle se remarque, ne peut faire supposer qu&apos;elle soit due &agrave; une cause traumatique, ni &agrave; l&apos;action d&apos;aucun instrument, d&apos;aucune application caustique ou corrosive. Tout est lisse comme si cette ouverture y avait &eacute;t&eacute; faite sans violence et depuis assez longtemps, avant la mort du sujet. On ne peut supposer davantage que cette ouverture soit le r&eacute;sultat de l&apos;application du tr&eacute;pan dont elle ne pr&eacute;sente point la forme.&raquo; Docteur HOUSSARD, <cite>&eacute;tude anatomique de la t&ecirc;te de saint Aubert</cite>. <br><font color="green">[2]</font> La mac&eacute;ration qui produisit le miracle rapport&eacute; ci-dessus rappelle les prodiges op&eacute;r&eacute;s par l&apos;eau dans laquelle on faisait tremper les os de saint Firmin. On vendait aux p&egrave;lerins des bouteilles de cette eau miraculeuse. Cf. <cite>Soc. Acad&eacute;m. de Laon</cite>, t. XVIII, &eacute;tude de M. MATTON. <br><font color="green">[This is how in the early years of the monastery, two religious were taken by an acute and strong fever. One of them asked his brothers &ldquo;<mark>to wash the head of saint Aubert and to give him to drink the liquor that they had used in washing him</mark>. [1]</font>&rdquo; He drank and was healed. The other monk, too soft &ldquo;and not well fortified by good sense,&rdquo; said that he would rather die than to drink liquor that had been distilled from the head of a dead man.&rdquo; He died eight days later. <br>Footnote <font color="green">[1]</font> The head of saint Aubert is preserved still at the basilica of Saint-Gervais in Avranches. Tradition has it that the archangel saint Michael, while appearing to saint Aubert, put his finger in the skull of the bishop who did listen to his commands. This curious relic shows us that the bone of the skull and of the face are still attached. The only things missing are the lower maxillary bone and the teeth of the upper jaw: &ldquo;During a first inspection we see towards the middle of the right parietal bone an oblong opening, from the back to the front, large enough to introduce a thumb. The rims of the opening are a bit thinner, smooth outside as inside. Nothing in the periphery of the opening, neither in the length of the bone, shows the action of an instrument, the application of something biting or corrosive. Everything is smooth as if this opening had been made without violence and a long time before the death of the subject. We can neither assume that this opening was the result of the application of a trephine of which it does not show the form.&rdquo; Docteur HOUSSARD, <cite>&eacute;tude anatomique de la t&ecirc;te de saint Aubert</cite>. <br><font color="green">[2]</font> The maceration that produces the miracle reported here <mark>resembles the effects produced by the waters in which one used to dip the bones of saint Firmin</mark>. This miraculous water was sold in bottles to the pilgrims. Cf. <cite>Soc. Acad&eacute;m. de Laon</cite>, t. XVIII, &eacute;tude de M. MATTON. <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 50-1</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Saint Aubert&apos;s day (10 September) is followed by Saint Firmin&apos;s (11 September). </mm> </dd></dl>
